a.html Online exhibition analyzing a Korean Bodhisattva sculpture]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120103093104/http://www.buddhanet.net/e-learning/history/tstang-txt.htm Buddhanet.net Ksitigarbha Bodhisattva]\n*[http://libmma.contentdm.oclc.org/cdm/ref/collection/p15324coll10/id/101557 ''Sacred visions : early paintings from central Tibet''], fully digitized text from The Metropolitan Museum of Art libraries\n\n{{Buddhism topics}}\n{{Bodhisattvas}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Bodhisattvas| ]]\n[[Category:Gender and Buddhism]]\n[[Category:Buddhist philosophical concepts]]\n[[Category:Buddhist titles]]\n", "name_user": "Gunkarta", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eIconography and the popular mind", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bodhisattva"}
{"title_page": "J\u014dgashima Lighthouse", "text_new": "{{more footnotes|date=April 2013}}\n{{Infobox lighthouse\n |name = J\u014dgashima Lighthouse<br />(\u57ce\u30f6\u5cf6\u706f\u53f0)\n | image_name = Jougashima toudai.JPG\n | caption = J\u014dgashima Lighthouse\n | location = [[Miura, Kanagawa|Miura]]<br /> [[Kanagawa Prefecture]]<br /> [[Japan]]\n | coordinates = {{coord|35|08|06.4|N|139|36|40.1|E|display=inline,title}}\n | pushpin_map = Japan\n | relief = 1\n | pushpin = lighthouse\n | yearbuilt = 1870 (first)\n | yearlit = 1925 (current)\n | automated = yes\n | yeardeactivated = \n | foundation = concrete base\n | construction = concrete tower\n | shape = cylindrical tower with balcony and lantern\n | marking = white tower and lantern\n | height = {{convert|11.5|m|ft}}\n | focalheight =  {{convert|30.1|m|ft}}\n | lens = 4th order [[Fresnel]]\n | intensity=400,000 candela\n | range = {{convert|16|nmi}}<ref>[http://yamatae.sakura.ne.jp/Lh3/joga.html Lighthouses in Japan]</ref>\n | characteristic = Fl W 15s\n| admiralty = M6343\n| canada = \n| NGA = 5368\n| ARLHS = JPN-203\n| USCG = \n| country = Japan\n| countrynumber = JCG-2407<ref>[https://www.unc.edu/~rowlett/lighthouse/jphn2a.htm Lighthouses Directory]</ref>\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''J\u014dgashima Lighthouse'''|\u57ce\u30f6\u5cf6\u706f\u53f0|J\u014dgashima t\u014ddai}} is a [[lighthouse]] located on the island of [[J\u014dgashima]] ({{Lang-ja|\u57ce\u30f6\u5cf6}}) in the city of [[Miura, Kanagawa|Miura]], [[Kanagawa Prefecture]], [[Japan]], off the southernmost and western tip of [[Miura Peninsula]], facing [[Sagami Bay]]. It is the fourth oldest western style lighthouse to be built in Japan, and the second oldest surviving to the present day.\n\n== History ==\nThe J\u014dgashima Lighthouse was one of eight lighthouses built in Japan under the provisions of the [[Anglo-Japanese Treaty of Amity and Commerce]] of 1858, signed by the [[Bakumatsu period]] [[Tokugawa Shogunate]]. The lighthouse was designed and constructed by [[o-yatoi gaikokujin|expatriate French engineer]] [[L\u00e9once Verny]]. Verny constructed another three lighthouses around [[Tokyo Bay]], and was also the engineer who built the nearby [[Yokosuka Naval Arsenal]] during his career in Japan.\n\n[[File:MisakiHarbour.jpg|thumb|left|The lighthouse on top of J\u014dgashima (seen here at the center of the photograph, from [[Misaki, Kanagawa|Misaki harbour]]).]]\nThe J\u014dgashima Lighthouse was completed on September 8, 1870 after the [[Meiji Restoration]], and was originally built of brick. The original structure was destroyed during the [[1923 Great Kant\u014d earthquake|Great Kant\u014d earthquake]] on September 1, 1923 and was replaced with the current reinforced-[[concrete]] round structure on August 1, 1925. In 1928, its light source was changed from [[acetylene]] to electric, greatly increasing its visibility.  The lighthouse has been unmanned since 1991.  It is currently maintained by the [[Japan Coast Guard]].\n\n== See also ==\n{{stack|{{Portal|Japan|Engineering}}}}\n* [[List of lighthouses in Japan]]\n\n== References ==\n*Pedlar, Neil. ''The Imported Pioneers: Westerners who Helped Build Modern Japan''. Routledge, 1990. {{ISBN|0-904404-51-X}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*  [http://www001.upp.so-net.ne.jp/yama/light.html#3 Lighthouses in Japan] {{in lang|ja}}\n\n{{Lighthouses of Japan}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jogashima Lighthouse}}\n[[Category:Lighthouses completed in 1870]]\n[[Category:Lighthouses completed in 1925]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Kanagawa Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Lighthouses in Japan]]\n\n\n{{lighthouse-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{more footnotes|date=April 2013}}\n{{Infobox lighthouse\n |name = J\u014dgashima Lighthouse<br /> ''Zy\u014dga Sima''<br />\u57ce\u30f6\u5cf6\u706f\u53f0\n | image_name = Jougashima toudai.JPG\n | caption = J\u014dgashima Lighthouse\n | location = [[Miura, Kanagawa|Miura]]<br /> [[Kanagawa Prefecture]]<br /> [[Japan]]\n | coordinates = {{coord|35|08|06.4|N|139|36|40.1|E|display=inline,title}}\n | pushpin_map = Japan\n | relief = 1\n | pushpin = lighthouse\n | yearbuilt = 1870 (first)\n | yearlit = 1925 (current)\n | automated = yes\n | yeardeactivated = \n | foundation = concrete base\n | construction = concrete tower\n | shape = cylindrical tower with balcony and lantern\n | marking = white tower and lantern\n | height = {{convert|11.5|m|ft}}\n | focalheight =  {{convert|30.1|m|ft}}\n | lens = 4th order [[Fresnel]]\n | intensity=400,000 candela\n | range = {{convert|16|nmi}}<ref>[http://yamatae.sakura.ne.jp/Lh3/joga.html Lighthouses in Japan]</ref>\n | characteristic = Fl W 15s\n| admiralty = M6343\n| canada = \n| NGA = 5368\n| ARLHS = JPN-203\n| USCG = \n| country = Japan\n| countrynumber = JCG-2407<ref>[https://www.unc.edu/~rowlett/lighthouse/jphn2a.htm Lighthouses Directory]</ref>\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''J\u014dgashima Lighthouse'''|\u57ce\u30f6\u5cf6\u706f\u53f0|J\u014dgashima t\u014ddai}} is a [[lighthouse]] located on the island of [[J\u014dgashima]] (in {{Lang-ja|\u57ce\u30f6\u5cf6}}) in the city of [[Miura, Kanagawa|Miura]], [[Kanagawa Prefecture]], [[Japan]], off the southernmost and western tip of [[Miura Peninsula]], facing [[Sagami Bay]]. It is the fourth oldest western style lighthouse to be built in Japan, and the second oldest surviving to the present day.\n\n== History ==\nThe J\u014dgashima Lighthouse was one of eight lighthouses built in Japan under the provisions of the [[Anglo-Japanese Treaty of Amity and Commerce]] of 1858, signed by the [[Bakumatsu period]] [[Tokugawa Shogunate]]. The lighthouse was designed and constructed by [[o-yatoi gaikokujin|expatriate French engineer]] [[L\u00e9once Verny]]. Verny constructed another three lighthouses around [[Tokyo Bay]], and was also the engineer who built the nearby [[Yokosuka Naval Arsenal]] during his career in Japan.\n\n[[File:MisakiHarbour.jpg|thumb|left|The lighthouse on top of J\u014dgashima (seen here at the center of the photograph, from [[Misaki, Kanagawa|Misaki harbour]]).]]\nThe J\u014dgashima Lighthouse was completed on September 8, 1870 after the [[Meiji Restoration]], and was originally built of brick. The original structure was destroyed during the [[1923 Great Kant\u014d earthquake|Great Kant\u014d earthquake]] on September 1, 1923 and was replaced with the current reinforced-[[concrete]] round structure on August 1, 1925. In 1928, its light source was changed from [[acetylene]] to electric, greatly increasing its visibility.  The lighthouse has been unmanned since 1991.  It is currently maintained by the [[Japan Coast Guard]].\n\n== See also ==\n{{stack|{{Portal|Japan|Engineering}}}}\n* [[List of lighthouses in Japan]]\n\n== References ==\n*Pedlar, Neil. ''The Imported Pioneers: Westerners who Helped Build Modern Japan''. Routledge, 1990. {{ISBN|0-904404-51-X}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*  [http://www001.upp.so-net.ne.jp/yama/light.html#3 Lighthouses in Japan] {{in lang|ja}}\n\n{{Lighthouses of Japan}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jogashima Lighthouse}}\n[[Category:Lighthouses completed in 1870]]\n[[Category:Lighthouses completed in 1925]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Kanagawa Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Lighthouses in Japan]]\n\n\n{{lighthouse-stub}}\n", "name_user": "ChromeGames923", "label": "safe", "comment": "Infobox title", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/J%C5%8Dgashima_Lighthouse"}
{"title_page": "Turgay Uzer", "text_new": "{{Infobox scientist\n|name = Ahmet Turgay Uzer\n|caption =Turgay Uzer\n|birth_date = February 1, 1952\n|birth_place = Samsun, Turkey\n|residence =[[Atlanta, Georgia]], [[United States]]\n|nationality =\n|field = [[Physics]], [[Chemistry]], [[Applied Mathematics]]\n|work_institution = [[Georgia Institute of Technology]]\n|alma_mater = [[Middle East Technical University]], [[Harvard]]\n|doctoral_advisor = \n|doctoral_students =\n|known_for  = [[Nonlinear dynamics]] and [[Chaos theory|chaos]] in [[classical mechanics]] and semiclassical mechanics applied to atomic systems.\n}}\n\n'''Ahmet Turgay Uzer''' is a Turkish-born [[United States|American]] [[theoretical physicist]].\n\nRegents' Professor Emeritus at [[Georgia Institute of Technology]] following [[Joseph Ford (physicist)]]. He has contributed in the field of atomic and molecular physics, [[nonlinear dynamics]] and chaos significantly.<ref>[https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=Turgay+Uzer&ie=UTF-8&oe=UTF-8&hl=en&btnG=Search Turgay Uzer on Google Scholar]</ref> His research on interplay between [[quantum dynamics]]\nand [[classical mechanics]], in the context of [[Chaos theory|chaos]] is considered to be novel in molecular and theoretical physics and chemistry.\n<!--\nDeleted image removed: [[Image:Tuzer.jpg|left|thumb|100px|Professor Turgay Uzer.]] -->\n\n== Academic career ==\n\nTurgay Uzer completed his bachelor's degree at Turkey's prestigious [[Middle East Technical University]]. According to [[Harvard University]] Library [http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1979PhDT.........7U] his doctoral thesis was entitled \"Photon and electron interactions with diatomic molecules.\" He defended his dissertation and graduated from Harvard University in 1979.\n\nBefore joining [[Georgia Tech]] in 1985 as an associate professor, he worked as a research fellow at [[University of Oxford]] 1979/81, [[Caltech]] 1982/1983, and as a research associate at [[University of Colorado at Boulder|University of Colorado]] 1983/85. Currently, he is a faculty member with the [http://www.cns.gatech.edu/ Center for Nonlinear Science] and\nfull professor of physics at [[Georgia Tech]].\n\nHis research areas are quite broad, but he has focused on the dynamics of intermolecular energy transfer, reaction dynamics, quantal manifestations of\nclassical mechanics, quantization of nonlinear systems, computational physics, molecular physics,\napplied mathematics.\n\n== Awards ==\n\nUzer was [[Alexander von Humboldt]]-Stiftung Foundation Fellow in 1993\u20131994 at\n[[Max Planck Institute]], Munich.\n\nUzer is of Turkish origin and was also awarded the prestigious Science award for his contributions to physics\nfrom the [[T\u00dcB\u0130TAK|Scientific and Technological Research Council (T\u00dcB\u0130TAK)]] [http://www.biltek.tubitak.gov.tr/oduller_en/previous_science.htm] in 1998.\n\n==Selected publications==\n\n===Books===\n* '''The Physics and Chemistry of Wave Packets''', with John Yeazell [https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=_sScnHz1kfsC&oi=fnd&pg=PP9&dq=Turgay+Uzer&ots=lRbbcuktgb&sig=eouJLWNs6M5yJfg491Jkca4Hf_U at books.google]\n* '''Lecture Notes on Atomic and Molecular Physics''' with \u015eakir Erko\u00e7 [https://books.google.com/books?id=KWssMj81fpkC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Lecture+Notes+on+Atomic+and+Molecular+Physics&lr=&sig=AsCyLPDzCqc8LLeL1E75nUJzauk at books.google]\n\n===Some of the seminal papers===\n\nUzer has more than 80 referenced Journal articles, in a number of highly respected scientific journals.\n* [http://link.aps.org/abstract/PRE/v48/p3414 appeared in PRE] Chaotic billiards with neutral boundaries\n* [http://www.sciencemag.org/cgi/content/abstract/253/5015/42 appeared in Science] Celestial Mechanics on a Microscopic Scale\n* [http://link.aip.org/link/?JCPSA6/81/5013/1 appeared in JCP] Quantization with operators appropriate to shapes of trajectories and classical perturbation theory\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.physics.gatech.edu/user/turgay-uzer Georgia Tech Homepage]\n* [http://www.cns.gatech.edu/CNS/Uzer03/images.html Physics Professor Turgay Uzer has been named Regents-reception]\n\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Uzer, Turgay}}\n[[Category:Turkish physicists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American physicists]]\n[[Category:Turkish chemists]]\n[[Category:Turkish mathematicians]]\n[[Category:Turkish academics]]\n[[Category:Turkish emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Atomic, molecular, and optical physics]]\n[[Category:Georgia Tech faculty]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Theoretical physicists]]\n[[Category:Computational chemists]]\n[[Category:American academics of Turkish descent]]\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox scientist\n|name = Ahmet Turgay Uzer\n|caption =Turgay Uzer\n|birth_date = February 1, 1952\n|birth_place = Samsun, Turkey\n|residence =[[Atlanta, Georgia]], [[United States]]\n|nationality =\n|field = [[Physics]], [[Chemistry]], [[Applied Mathematics]]\n|work_institution = [[Georgia Institute of Technology]]\n|alma_mater = [[Middle East Technical University]], [[Harvard]]\n|doctoral_advisor = \n|doctoral_students =\n|known_for  = [[Nonlinear dynamics]] and [[Chaos theory|chaos]] in [[classical mechanics]] and semiclassical mechanics applied to atomic systems.\n}}\n\n'''Ahmet Turgay Uzer''' is a Turkish born [[United States|American]] [[theoretical physicist]].\n\nRegents' Professor Emeritus at [[Georgia Institute of Technology]] following [[Joseph Ford (physicist)]]. He has contributed in the field of atomic and molecular physics, [[nonlinear dynamics]] and chaos significantly.<ref>[https://scholar.google.com/scholar?q=Turgay+Uzer&ie=UTF-8&oe=UTF-8&hl=en&btnG=Search Turgay Uzer on Google Scholar]</ref> His research on interplay between [[quantum dynamics]]\nand [[classical mechanics]], in the context of [[Chaos theory|chaos]] is considered to be novel in molecular and theoretical physics and chemistry.\n<!--\nDeleted image removed: [[Image:Tuzer.jpg|left|thumb|100px|Professor Turgay Uzer.]] -->\n\n== Academic career ==\n\nTurgay Uzer completed his bachelor's degree at Turkey's prestigious [[Middle East Technical University]]. According to [[Harvard University]] Library [http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/1979PhDT.........7U] his doctoral thesis was entitled \"Photon and electron interactions with diatomic molecules.\" He defended his dissertation and graduated from Harvard University in 1979.\n\nBefore joining [[Georgia Tech]] in 1985 as an associate professor, he worked as a research fellow at [[University of Oxford]] 1979/81, [[Caltech]] 1982/1983, and as a research associate at [[University of Colorado at Boulder|University of Colorado]] 1983/85. Currently, he is a faculty member with the [http://www.cns.gatech.edu/ Center for Nonlinear Science] and\nfull professor of physics at [[Georgia Tech]].\n\nHis research areas are quite broad but he has focused on the dynamics of intermolecular energy transfer, reaction dynamics, quantal manifestations of\nclassical mechanics, quantization of nonlinear systems, computational physics, molecular physics,\napplied mathematics.\n\n== Awards ==\n\nUzer was [[Alexander von Humboldt]]-Stiftung Foundation Fellow in 1993\u20131994 at\n[[Max Planck Institute]], Munich.\n\nUzer is of Turkish origin and was also awarded the prestigious Science award for his contributions to Physics\nfrom the [[T\u00dcB\u0130TAK|Scientific and Technological Research Council (T\u00dcB\u0130TAK)]] [http://www.biltek.tubitak.gov.tr/oduller_en/previous_science.htm] in 1998.\n\n==Selected publications==\n\n===Books===\n* '''The Physics and Chemistry of Wave Packets''', with John Yeazell [https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=_sScnHz1kfsC&oi=fnd&pg=PP9&dq=Turgay+Uzer&ots=lRbbcuktgb&sig=eouJLWNs6M5yJfg491Jkca4Hf_U at books.google]\n* '''Lecture Notes on Atomic and Molecular Physics''' with \u015eakir Erko\u00e7 [https://books.google.com/books?id=KWssMj81fpkC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Lecture+Notes+on+Atomic+and+Molecular+Physics&lr=&sig=AsCyLPDzCqc8LLeL1E75nUJzauk at books.google]\n\n===Some of the seminal papers===\n\nUzer has more than 80 referenced Journal articles, in a number of highly respected scientific journals.\n* [http://link.aps.org/abstract/PRE/v48/p3414 appeared in PRE] Chaotic billiards with neutral boundaries\n* [http://www.sciencemag.org/cgi/content/abstract/253/5015/42 appeared in Science] Celestial Mechanics on a Microscopic Scale\n* [http://link.aip.org/link/?JCPSA6/81/5013/1 appeared in JCP] Quantization with operators appropriate to shapes of trajectories and classical perturbation theory\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.physics.gatech.edu/user/turgay-uzer Georgia Tech Homepage]\n* [http://www.cns.gatech.edu/CNS/Uzer03/images.html Physics Professor Turgay Uzer has been named Regents-reception]\n\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Uzer, Turgay}}\n[[Category:Turkish physicists]]\n[[Category:21st-century American physicists]]\n[[Category:Turkish chemists]]\n[[Category:Turkish mathematicians]]\n[[Category:Turkish academics]]\n[[Category:Turkish emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Atomic, molecular, and optical physics]]\n[[Category:Georgia Tech faculty]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Theoretical physicists]]\n[[Category:Computational chemists]]\n[[Category:American academics of Turkish descent]]\n[[Category:1952 births]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "cap, punct", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Turgay_Uzer"}
